As you know I can see a violent change from the virtuous cycle (of inflows) to a vicious cycle (of outflows). Given the constituent holdings' illiquidity - it is possible that a disruption in the disruptor's ETF occurs in which there is more volatility in $ARK than her holdings.

My analysis is about making money on the shares of one of her ETFs $ARK. Specifically my short in $ARK. And you have read the reasons why I shorted this name. Nothing to do with AUM or her success. Investing (long or short) is not about the rear view mirror. So far it has worked
And Tepper is Tepper And Druckenmiller is Druckenmiller And Cooperman is Cooperman Ecletic stock and asset class selection. Consistent outperformance --absolutely, relatively and adjusted for risk.

I don't think she is nutty at all. Just giving the performance facts and discussing popularity. 2020 was a spectacular year for ARK. Problem is, in the last 12 months or so, assets under management rose from $10 billion to $60 billion. Alot of "Johnny Come Latelies."

Memo to Josh Brown @ScottWapnerCNBC Cathie Wood underperformed her benchmark consistently at Alliance Bernstein while managing thematic portfolios. Since she started ARK in 2014 - she had two sensational years (2017 and 2020). @cnbcfastmoney
